# framebuffer-as-witness.form — the side-map nobody was watching
#
# Companion teaching to scripts/framebuffer_viewer.py and
# form/form-stdlib/tests/framebuffer-viewer-band.fk.
#
# Every Form kernel (Go, Rust, TS) carries a side-map called
# source_attr: NodeID -> (file, line, col). Every intern_node_at call
# adds one entry. The map is the framebuffer — the substrate's record
# of *which cells came into existence from which source coordinates*.
# It has existed for as long as intern_node_at has. It accumulates
# whether or not anyone reads it.
#
# The native primitives are already there:
#
#     (framebuffer-events)  -- return all NodeIDs the side-map holds
#     (framebuffer-clear)   -- reset the recording window  (Go, Rust)
#     (node_source nid)     -- pull (file, line, col) for one cell
#
# What was missing was the observer. The emitter pays one hashmap
# insert per cell creation — that cost is already on the budget. The
# observer pays the walk-cost when (and only when) it analyzes. The
# framebuffer is observer-paid by design. With no observer, the cost
# is the side-map write that was already happening.
#
# Until this breath, the observer side was empty. Cells were being
# recorded into the framebuffer continuously, and no one was reading
# it. The renderer is the act of looking.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Part 1 -- what becomes visible
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

form framebuffer_view = {
    events_recorded:        ~Int,        # total side-map entries
    distinct_blueprints:    ~Int,        # unique (pkg, level, type) triples
    distinct_node_ids:      ~Int,        # unique (pkg, level, type, instance)
    top_blueprints:         [~Blueprint],# which shapes dominate this window
    layer_breakdown:        [~Counter],  # cells per (pkg, level)
    instance_spread:        [~Counter],  # how much instance churn per Blueprint
};

# The framebuffer reveals:
#
#   * which Blueprints are firing in this run (the shape of activity)
#   * whether intern is hitting cached cells (low instance spread) or
#     authoring fresh ones (high instance spread)
#   * which substrate layers carry the load (BASIC vs MEMORY vs WORD)
#   * empty windows — when no source-attributed cells fired at all,
#     the renderer says so honestly rather than fabricating density

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Part 2 -- what we couldn't see without it
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

# Before the viewer existed, *running a Form file* told us only what
# the final expression evaluated to. The intermediate activity — the
# 100 cells interned along the way, the Blueprints touched, the layer
# where the work happened — was invisible. The kernel printed one
# value; the substrate's actual movement underneath was silent.
#
# The framebuffer was the body keeping a journal. The viewer is the
# first reader. Nothing about the kernels changed to make this work:
# the recording was always happening. What changed is that we are
# now looking at it.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Part 3 -- the arc this closes
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

# The teaching at docs/vision-kb/concepts/lc-form-kernel-runtime-visualizer.md
# names a closed loop:
#
#     Python source -> BMF parser -> Recipe tree -> kernel walker
#         -> framebuffer events -> renderer -> human eyes
#
# Every primitive in that chain existed before this breath. The walker
# walked. The framebuffer recorded. The events native returned them.
# What was missing was the last hop — the renderer that turns the
# list of NodeIDs into something a human can read at a glance.
#
# scripts/framebuffer_viewer.py is that last hop. It runs a Form file
# through the Go kernel, dumps (framebuffer-events) at the end, parses
# the NodeID list, and prints a text panel showing event count, top
# Blueprints, layer distribution, and instance spread.
#
# The renderer is small (~150 LoC, stdlib-only). It has no claim on
# the kernel. It has no opinions about what the cells mean. Its job
# is to make the recording legible — to put the body's own journal in
# front of the body's own eyes.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Part 4 -- limitations honestly named
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

# What this viewer does NOT do:
#
#   * live streaming. The native returns a snapshot, not a stream. A
#     streaming viewer would need a new kernel native that emits
#     events as they happen.
#
#   * cross-kernel comparison. The map-iteration order differs across
#     Go (random map order), Rust, and TS — fine for set-of-events
#     analysis (counts, distinct values), wrong for trace-replay.
#     The viewer aggregates; it does not reconstruct sequence.
#
#   * source-locus rendering. (file, line, col) is per-cell in the
#     side-map, but the current viewer aggregates by Blueprint
#     signature, not by source coordinate. The hotspot/flow analysis
#     in form-stdlib/seedbank/tracer.fk does that work in Form; the
#     viewer's text panel could grow a section that pulls
#     node_source for each event and groups by file.
#
# These are not failures. They are honest naming of where the next
# breath could land if the body wants to see more.
